[[File:Mining and Scientific Press 1885 nameplate.jpg|thumb|Nameplate of the ''Mining and Scientific Press'' in 1885]]
[[File:Poly Masthead.svg|thumb|Nameplate of ''The Rensselaer Polytechnic'' student newspaper]]

In American usage, a periodical publication's '''nameplate''' is its designed title as it appears on the front page or cover. In the United Kingdom, as well as in many other [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] nations, this is known as the publication's '''masthead'''.<ref name=Guardian>[http://image.guardian.co.uk/sys-files/Guardian/documents/2011/08/26/EducCentNewsterminology.pdf The Guardian: ''Newspaper terminology''] Linked 2013-06-16</ref><ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/6JGcp6zb0?url=http://image.guardian.co.uk/sys-files/Guardian/documents/2011/08/26/EducCentNewsterminology.pdf ''Newspaper terminology'' Archived pdf at WebCitation.]</ref>

In American usage, the term [[Masthead (publishing)|masthead]] refers to a printed list – published in a fixed position in each edition of a periodical – of its owners, departments, officers, and address details.<ref>Funk & Wagnall's Standard Dictionary, New York 1960</ref><ref>E.g., [https://www.nytimes.com/ref/membercenter/masthead_newspaper.html masthead of The New York Times]</ref> This same feature is in British English usage referred to as the periodical's [[imprint (UK printing)|imprint]].<ref name="Guardian"/>

