==North America==
===Bermuda===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Bermuda}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal<br>Buying sex legal<br>Brothels illegal<br>Procuring illegal
}}
{{main|Prostitution in the British Overseas Territories#Bermuda}}
Prostitution is legal in [[Bermuda]] but related activities such as running a brothel are illegal under the Criminal Code.<ref>{{cite web|title=Criminal code of Bermuda|url=http://www.bermudalaws.bm/Laws/Consolidated%20Laws/Criminal%20Code%20Act%201907.pdf|website=Bermuda Laws|accessdate=25 February 2018}}</ref> Women coming to the island to work as prostitutes, or is a known prostitute, may be refused entry under the immigration laws.<ref>{{cite book|title=Bermuda Immigration Laws, Policy and Regulations Handbook: Strategic Information and Regulations|date=2013|publisher=Lulu|isbn=9781438782171|url=https://books.google.com/?id=AoN_CgAAQBAJ&pg=PA83&lpg=PA83&dq=prostitution+in+Bermuda#v=onepage&q=prostitution%20in%20Bermuda&f=false|language=en}}</ref> Many of the prostitutes in the country are from Philippines, Dominican Republic and Panama.<ref>{{cite web|title=BERMUDA-IMMIGRATION-Angry Filipinos pull out of Bermuda Day parade|url=https://antiguaobserver.com/bermuda-immigration-angry-filipinos-pull-out-of-bermuda-day-parade/|website=Antigua Observer Newspaper|accessdate=25 February 2018|date=10 May 2010}}</ref> In 2010 the visa requirements for people from these countries was changed to attempt to curb prostitution.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bermuda Visa Rules for Panama Philippines Dominican Republic|url=http://bernews.com/2010/03/new-visas-reports-of-prostitution-sham-marriages/|website=Bernews|accessdate=25 February 2018|date=30 March 2010}}</ref> Street prostitution occurs in the capital, [[Hamilton, Bermuda|Hamilton]], on Front Street.<ref>{{cite web|title=Reports of prostitutes on Front Street sparks concern {{!}} The Royal Gazette:Bermuda News|url=http://www.royalgazette.com/article/20111130/NEWS/711309938|website=The Royal Gazette|accessdate=25 February 2018|date=30 November 2011}}</ref>
{{clear}}

===Canada===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Canada}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal<br>Buying sex illegal<br>Brothels illegal<br>Procuring illegal<br>Solicitation illegal
}}
{{main|Prostitution in Canada}}
Prostitution was traditionally legal as there were no laws prohibiting the exchange of sex for money or other consideration. On 20 December 2013, the [[Supreme Court of Canada]] found the laws prohibiting [[brothels]], public communication for the purpose of prostitution, and living on the profits of prostitution to be unconstitutional. The ruling gave the [[Parliament of Canada|Canadian parliament]] 12 months to rewrite the prostitution laws with a stay of effect so that the current laws remain in force.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-25468587 | work=BBC News | title=Canada Supreme Court strikes down prostitution laws | date=2013-12-20}}</ref> Amending legislation came into effect on 6 December 2014, which made the purchase of sexual services illegal, using the [[Prostitution in Sweden|Swedish approach]].<ref>{{cite newspaper|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2014/12/03/controversial_prostitution_law_introduced_on_day_of_action_on_violence_against_women.html|title=Controversial prostitution law introduced on day of action on violence against women|author=Stephanie Levitz|date=3 December 2014|newspaper=Toronto Star|accessdate=26 October 2017}}</ref>

===Greenland===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Greenland}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution illegal<br>Buying sex legal
}}
Prostitution in [[Greenland]] is illegal.<ref>{{cite news|title=Small-Town Greenland Prepares for Influx of Foreign Workers|url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/small-town-greenland-prepares-for-influx-of-foreign-workers_1480624.html|author=Susanne Willgren|newspaper=The Epoch Times|date=31 October 2012|accessdate=28 October 2017}}</ref> Although the country is subject to the [[law of Denmark]] in most areas of legislation, Denmark's decriminalization of prostitution in 1999 has not been applied in Greenland.<ref name=H&S>{{cite report|title=Prostitution in the Nordic Countries|url=http://norden.diva-portal.org/smash/get/diva2:701621/FULLTEXT01.pdf|location=Stockholm|date=16–17 October 2008|first1=Charlotta|last1=Holmström|first2=May-Len|last2=Skilbrei|publisher=Nordic Council of Ministers|isbn=978-92-893-1930-0}}</ref> In addition, Greenland is exempt from the obligations of the [[Protocol to Prevent, Suppress and Punish Trafficking in Persons, especially Women and Children|Palermo Protocol on human trafficking]] to which Denmark is a signatory,<ref name=H&S/> but there is little evidence of human trafficking in Greenland.<ref>{{cite report|title=Human Trafficking as a Human Rights Issue And Policy Responses of Arctic Nations|url=https://www.rha.is/static/files/NRF/OpenAssemblies/Anchorage2008/a/5th_nrf_anc_2008_footen_bromfield_human_trafficking.pdf|first=Nicole Footen|last=Bromfield|publisher=Virginia Commonwealth University|page=10|accessdate=28 October 2017}}</ref> A report published in 2008 indicated that Greenland had no signs of visible or organised prostitution, no services directed specifically at prostitutes and no instances of prostitution-related court cases. It did, however, refer to claims that [[transactional sex]] had sometimes been used, for example, in return for temporary housing.<ref name=H&S/> In a tradition associated with Greenland's [[Inuit]] people, hosts have been reported to have offered their wives to guests in a form of "hospitable prostitution".<ref>{{cite book|title=Criminal Woman, the Prostitute, and the Normal Woman|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=S3g29DlTxNsC|first1=Cesare|last1=Lombroso|first2=Guglielmo|last2=Ferrero|publisher=Duke University Press|year=2004|isbn=9780822332466|page=101}}</ref> The colonists who founded the country's capital [[Nuuk]] in 1728 included prostitutes among their number.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Wurm|first1=Stephen A.|last2=Mühlhäusler|first2=Peter |last3=Tyron|first3=Darrell T.|title=Atlas of Languages of Intercultural Communication in the Pacific, Asia, and the Americas, International Council for Philosophy and Humanistic Studies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=glU0vte5gSkC|series=Volume 2, Part 1 Volume 13 of Trends in Linguistics|year=1996|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|isbn=978-3-11-013417-9|page=1051}}</ref>

===Mexico===
{{main|Prostitution in Mexico}}
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Mexico}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal under Federal law<br>Each state enacts its own prostitution laws<br>Prostitution is legal and regulated in 13 states<br>Buying sex legal
}}
Prostitution in [[Mexico]] is legal under Federal law. Each of the 31 [[List of states of Mexico|states]] enacts its own prostitution laws and policies.<ref name="spl" /> 13 of the states of Mexico allow and regulate prostitution.<ref>[[Ronald Weitzer|Weitzer, Ronald]]. 2013. ''Legalizing Prostitution: From Illicit Vice to Lawful Business''. ([http://www.businessinsider.com.au/galactic-zone-shows-why-we-should-legalize-prostitution-2013-10 Excerpt])</ref> Prostitution involving minors under 18 is illegal.
Some Mexican cities have enacted "tolerance zones" ("zonas de tolerancia") which allow [[regulated prostitution]] and function as [[red light district]]s. In [[Tuxtla Gutiérrez]], capital of the state of [[Chiapas]], there is a state-run brothel at the ''Zona Galáctica''.<ref name="zona">{{cite web|last1=Weitzer|first1=Ronald|title=Mexico's State-Run Brothel Shows Us The Benefits Of Making Prostitution Legal|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/galactic-zone-shows-why-we-should-legalize-prostitution-2013-10?IR=T|website=Business Insider|accessdate=22 April 2018|date=29 October 2013}}</ref> In most parts of the country, pimping is illegal, although pimp-worker relationships still occur, sometimes under female pimps called "madrotas".<ref>Patty Kelly, Lydia's Open Door: Inside Mexico's Most Modern Brothel (Berkeley: University of California Press, 2008), 126.</ref> The government provides shelter for former prostitutes.<ref>{{cite news|title= Elderly ex-prostitutes|work=[[Reuters]]|date=2007-10-26|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSN2020179420070620
}}</ref>
{{clear}}

===United States===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|United States}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution illegal except in licensed brothels in certain rural counties of Nevada<br>Buying sex illegal except in licensed brothels in certain rural counties of Nevada<br>Brothels illegal except for certain rural counties of Nevada where brothels are licensed and regulated<br>Procuring illegal<br>Solicitation illegal
}}
{{Main|Prostitution in the United States}}
Prostitution laws in the United States are determined at the state level. The practice is illegal in all but one of its 50 states and is illegal in all U.S. territories.

[[Nevada]] is the only [[Political divisions of the United States|U.S. jurisdiction]] which allows some legal prostitution in some of its counties. Currently 7 out of Nevada's 16 counties have active brothels. Prostitution outside these brothels is illegal throughout the state; prostitution is illegal in the major metropolitan areas ([[Las Vegas metropolitan area|Las Vegas]], [[Reno]], and [[Carson City]]). Prostitution is heavily regulated by the state of Nevada.

See [[Prostitution in Nevada]].
{{clear}}

==Central America==

===Belize===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Belize}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal<br>Buying sex illegal<br>Brothels illegal<br>Procuring illegal<br>Solicitation illegal
}}
{{main|Prostitution in Belize}}
Prostitution is legal in [[Belize]], but the buying of sexual services is not.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Flowers|first1=Benjamin|title=Regional prostitution laws challenged but sex work already legal in Belize|url=http://www.reporter.bz/front-page/regional-prostitution-laws-challenged-but-sex-work-already-legal-in-belize/|website=The Reporter Newspaper|accessdate=31 December 2017|date=22 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Prostitution in San Pedro|url=http://ambergrisdaily.com/ambergris-caye-stories/prostitution-in-san-pedro/|website=Ambergris Daily|accessdate=31 December 2017|date=2 August 2012}}</ref> Associated activities such as operating a [[brothel]], loitering for the purposes of prostitution and soliciting sex are also illegal.<ref name="spl">{{cite web |url= http://spl.ids.ac.uk/sexworklaw/countries |title= Sex Work Law |last= |first= |date= |website= Sexuality, Poverty and Law Programme |publisher= |access-date= 25 November 2017 |quote= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.channel5belize.com/archives/61581 |title=Special Envoy for Women and Children focus on sex predators &#124; Channel5Belize.com |publisher=Edition.channel5belize.com |date=2011-10-05 |accessdate=2012-05-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guardian.bz/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=3858:special-envoy-lobbying-for-harsher-laws-on-sex-crimes-against-children&catid=59:other-news&Itemid=88 |title=Special Envoy Lobbying for Harsher Laws on Sex Crimes against Children - The Guardian Newspaper |publisher=Guardian.bz |date=2011-10-06 |accessdate=2012-05-26}}</ref><ref name="cnn">{{cite web|url=http://ireport.cnn.com/docs/DOC-466131|title=Vivian Trill Report San Pedro, Ambergris Caye, Belize|publisher=|accessdate=27 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=eGCZmN2MPaUC&pg=PA31&lpg=PA31&dq=Prostitution%20in%20Belize#v=onepage&q=Prostitution%20in%20Belize&f=false|title=Gender, Sexuality and HIV Risk in Belize: A Mixed Methods Study|first=Jennifer Louise|last=Simmons|date=1 January 2008|publisher=ProQuest|accessdate=27 January 2017|via=Google Books|isbn=9780549724070}}</ref>

Prostitution is widespread and takes place on the streets and in brothels, bars, nightclubs and hotels.

Although denied by the government,<ref name="ramos">{{cite web|last1=Ramos|first1=Adele|title=Belize "sex paradise"?|url=http://amandala.com.bz/news/belize-sex-paradise/|website=Amandala Newspaper|accessdate=31 December 2017|date=14 February 2014}}</ref> the country is a destination for [[sex tourism]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.7newsbelize.com/sstory.php?nid=539&frmsrch=1|publisher=7 News Belize|title=Belizean Women Being Recruited To Work as Tourism Prostitutes|date=12 April 2007}}</ref><ref name="ramos" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Prostitution and Sex in Belize|url=http://guide2belize.com/belize-prostitution/|website=Guide2Belize|accessdate=31 December 2017}}</ref> [[Child sex tourism]] is a problem,<ref name="amand">{{cite newspaper|url=http://amandala.com.bz/news/child-sex-tourism-an-emerging-trend-in-belize/ |title=Child Sex Tourism "an emerging trend in Belize"|newspaper=Amandala Newspaper|date=18 June 2010|author=Adele Ramos}}</ref> primarily by visitors from the [[United States]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Belize 2017 Trafficking in Persons Report|url=https://www.state.gov/j/tip/rls/tiprpt/countries/2017/271146.htm|website=U.S. Department of State|accessdate=31 December 2017}}</ref>
{{clear}}

===Costa Rica===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Costa Rica}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal<br>Buying sex legal<br>Brothels illegal<br>Procuring illegal
