===El Salvador===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|El Salvador}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal under national law but may be prohibited by local laws<br>Buying sex legal under national law but may be prohibited by local laws<br>Brothels legal under national law but may be prohibited by local laws<br>Procuring illegal
}}
{{main|Prostitution in El Salvador}}
Prostitution itself is not prohibited by national law,<ref name="procon" /> but may be prohibited by local municipal ordinances.<ref name="red">{{cite web|last1=van Wanrooij|first1=Dennis |title=OTS: Mapping Human Rights Violations Against Sex Workers in El Salvador  - Red Umbrella Fund|url=http://www.redumbrellafund.org/ots-mapping-human-rights-violations-sex-workers-el-salvador/|website=Red Umbrella Fund|accessdate=31 December 2017|date=2 March 2015}}</ref> Municipal ordinances may also prohibit the purchase of sexual services.<ref name="red" /> Related activities such as facilitating, promoting or giving incentives to a person to work as a prostitute (pimping) are illegal. The prostitution of children (those under 18) is also illegal.<ref name="procon" /> Brothel ownership, however, is legal.<ref name="procon" /> There are no specific laws against human trafficking, but any criminal offence that includes ‘commerce in women or children’ requires sentencing to be increased by 30%.<ref name="dismal">{{cite web|title=Prostitution in El Salvador, San Salvador|url=http://www.dismalworld.com/prostitution-in-el-salvador-san-salvador/|website=Dismal World|accessdate=1 January 2018|date=25 January 2008}}</ref>

Those municipalities that do not prohibit sex work often set up zones for sex workers away from schools and churches.<ref name="procon" /> In the San Esteban area of [[San Salvador]], 17 brothels were forcibly closed in August 1998 for being too close to schools and churches.<ref>{{cite web|title=EL SALVADOR: AUTHORITIES ORDER CLOSURE OF BROTHELS|url=http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/youtube/0e6f64282022994b907a75ceaef2ccb5|website=AP Archive|accessdate=31 December 2017|date=31 August 1998}}</ref>
{{clear}}

===Guatemala===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Guatemala}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal<br>Buying sex legal<br>Brothels legal<br>Procuring illegal
}}
{{main|Prostitution in Guatemala}}
Prostitution itself is legal but procuring is prohibited.<ref name="procon" /> There is an offence of “aggravated procuring” where a minor is involved.<ref name="ips">{{cite web|url=http://www.ipsnews.net/2006/10/guatemala-where-sexual-exploitation-of-minors-is-not-a-crime/|title=GUATEMALA: Where Sexual Exploitation of Minors Is Not a Crime - Inter Press Service|publisher=|accessdate=27 January 2017}}</ref> Keeping a [[brothel]] is not prohibited.<ref name="procon" />

Prostitution is widespread in Guatemala; [[Guatemala City]] alone has 9 [[red-light district]]s,<ref name="wnn">{{cite web|last1=Wallace Bowman|first1=Hannah|title=Guatemala women sex-workers live in a dangerous 'twilight' world - Woman News Network (WNN)|url=https://womennewsnetwork.net/2014/03/17/guatemala-women-sex-workers-world/|website=Woman News Network (WNN)|accessdate=2 January 2018|date=17 March 2014}}</ref> including La Linea, El Trebol and Parque Concordia.<ref name="mujer">{{cite web|title=MuJER Guatemala - Our story|url=http://mujerguatemala.org/about-us/our-story/|website=MuJER Guatemala|accessdate=2 January 2018}}</ref> Statistics from the Vigilancia Centinela de las Infecciones de Transmisión Sexual (VICITS) sexual health clinics from 2007-2011, showed 10.8 of the sex workers worked on the streets, the rest working indoors at strip clubs, brothels based at residential homes, bars etc.<ref name="plos">{{cite journal|last1=Morales-Miranda|first1=Sonia|last2=Jacobson|first2=Jerry O.|last3=Loya-Montiel|first3=Itzel|last4=Mendizabal-Burastero|first4=Ricardo|last5=Galindo-Arandi|first5=César|last6=Flores|first6=Carlos|last7=Chen|first7=Sanny Y.|title=Scale-Up, Retention and HIV/STI Prevalence Trends among Female Sex Workers Attending VICITS Clinics in Guatemala|pmc=4148235|journal=PLoS ONE|volume=9|issue=8|pages=e103455|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0103455|pmid=25167141|date=28 August 2014}}</ref>
{{clear}}

===Honduras===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Honduras}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal<br>Buying sex legal<br>Brothels illegal<br>Procuring illegal
}}
{{main|Prostitution in Honduras}}
Prostitution is currently legal in [[Honduras]].<ref name="chartsbin" /> Because there is no law prohibiting prostitution, it is a prevalent form of occupation, especially amongst women and teenagers in cities. Although similar institutions such as brothel ownership and pimping are illegal, prostitution has remained largely unchecked by the government.

Lack of enforcement of current laws has created a profitable business out of prostitution - one in which both adults and children are a part. There are many causes to the high rates of involvement amongst the women and teens in cities, but the main reason is the high poverty levels. Participants see sex work as a viable option to escape poverty.

===Nicaragua===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Nicaragua}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal<br>Buying sex legal<br>Brothels illegal<br>Procuring illegal
}}
{{main|Prostitution in Nicaragua}}
Prostitution is legal, but promoting prostitution and procuring are prohibited.<ref name="state1">[https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2008/wha/119167.htm 2008 Human Rights Report: Nicaragua]. State.gov. Retrieved on 2011-03-30.</ref><ref name="procon" /> The minimum age for prostitutes is 14 years old.<ref name="state1" /> It was estimated in 2015 that were around 15,000 prostitutes in the country.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Custer|first1=Jeff|title=Nicaragua trains sex workers as judicial facilitators - Inside Costa Rica|url=http://insidecostarica.com/2015/06/04/nicaragua-trains-sex-workers-judicial-facilitators/|website=Inside Costa Rica|accessdate=2 January 2018|date=4 June 2015}}</ref>

Prostitution is common in [[Managua]]. Prostitutes work on the streets, in nightclubs and bars, or in massage parlors.

Prostitutes are known locally as "zorras".<ref>{{cite web|title=Live in Nicaragua - The Lay of the Land|url=http://www.liveinnicaragua.com/pages/chapter01.html|website=Live in Nicaragua|accessdate=2 January 2018|language=en-gb}}</ref>

===Panama===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Panama}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal and regulated<br>Buying sex legal<br>Brothels legal and regulated<br>Procuring illegal
}}
{{main|Prostitution in Panama}}
Prostitution is legal and [[Regulated prostitution|regulated]].<ref name="spl" /> Prostitutes are required to register and carry identification cards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepanamanews.com/pn/v_11/issue_07/frontpage.html|title=Is this the time or place to publish the profane?|publisher=thepanamanews.com|date=|accessdate=2013-12-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050829070851/http://www.thepanamanews.com/pn/v_11/issue_07/frontpage.html|archive-date=2005-08-29|deadurl=yes|df=}}</ref> However, the majority of prostitutes are not registered.<ref name="spl" /> 2,650 sex workers were registered with the government in 2008, but there was no accurate information regarding the total number of persons practising prostitution in the country.<ref>[https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2008/wha/119168.htm 2008 Human Rights Report: Panama]. State.gov (2009-02-25). Retrieved on 2011-03-30.</ref> Some estimate put the number of unregistered prostitutes at 4,000.<ref name="panguide">{{cite web|last1=Winner|first1=Don|title=Hookers, Hookers, Everywhere... Sex Tourism in Panama|url=http://www.panama-guide.com/article.php/20070512185127612|website=Panama-Guide|accessdate=20 December 2017|date=12 May 2007}}</ref>

The main area of prostitution in [[Panama City]] is El Cangrejo.<ref name="liveinvest">{{cite web|title=Fantastic Food, Expats, Einstein's Head, And Hookers—Exploring The Streets Of El Cangrejo|url=https://www.liveandinvestoverseas.com/in-focus-panama/el-cangrejo-panama-city-food-friends-and-entertainment/|website=Live and Invest Overseas|accessdate=20 December 2017|date=3 December 2015}}</ref><ref name="huff">{{cite web|last1=Peddicord|first1=Kathleen|title=10 Things To See And Do In Panama City's Rowdiest, Bawdiest Zone|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/kathleen-peddicord/10-top-things-to-see-and-_b_5954516.html|website=Huffington Post|accessdate=20 December 2017|date=6 December 2017}}</ref> Street prostitution also occurs on Avenida Mexico, Central Avenue and Avenida Perú,<ref name="clinic">{{cite web|title=Panama's rising prostitution pressures health center|url=http://www.newsroompanama.com/news/panama/panamas-rising-prostitution-pressures-health-clinic|website=Newsroom Panama|accessdate=20 December 2017|date=8 August 2017}}</ref>
{{clear}}

==South America==

===Argentina===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Argentina}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal under Federal law but illegal under local law in some areas<br>Buying sex legal<br>Brothels illegal<br>Procuring illegal
}}
{{main|prostitution in Argentina}}
Prostitution (exchanging sex for money) is legal under Federal law. Article 19 of the [[Constitution of Argentina|constitution]] states: ''"The private actions of people that do not offend in any way the public order and morality, nor damage a third person, are only reserved to God, and are exempt from the authority of the magistrates."''<ref name="procon" /> Organised prostitution (brothels, prostitution rings and pimping) is illegal.<ref name="danger">{{cite web|url=https://history.osu.edu/publications/sex-and-danger-buenos-aires-prostitution-family-and-nation-argentina|title=Sex and Danger in Buenos Aires: Prostitution, Family, and Nation in Argentina - Department of History|website=History.osu.edu|accessdate=9 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/americas/7793183.stm|title=BBC NEWS - Americas - Dark side of Argentine sex city|website=News.bbc.co.uk|accessdate=9 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Reed Lindsay in Buenos Aires |url=https://www.theguardian.com/argentina/story/0,11439,1130610,00.html |title=Argentina's prostitutes get militant &#124; World news &#124; The Observer |publisher=Guardian |date=2004-01-25 |accessdate=2013-08-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.infoleg.gov.ar/infolegInternet/anexos/15000-19999/16546/texact.htm |title=Codigo Penal De La Nacion Argentina |publisher=Infoleg.gov.ar |date= |accessdate=2013-08-01}}</ref><ref name=USDSHRR>{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2008/wha/119145.htm |title=2008 Human Rights Reports: Argentina |publisher=State.gov |date=2009-02-25 |accessdate=2011-10-01}}</ref> In addition, individual [[Provinces of Argentina|provinces]] may place further restriction on the trade.<ref name="panam">{{cite web|last1=Dubove|first1=Adam|title=Argentinean Sex Workers Demand the Right to Sell Their Own Bodies|url=https://panampost.com/adam-dubove/2015/12/04/argentinean-sex-workers-demand-the-right-to-exploit-their-own-bodies/|website=PanAm Post|accessdate=15 December 2017|date=4 December 2015}}</ref> For example in [[San Juan Province, Argentina|San Juan]], publicly offering sex services for money if punishable by up to 20 days in jail.<ref name="panam" /> In 2012, newspapers were banned from carrying classified-ads offering sexual services.<ref name="panam" />

===Bolivia===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Bolivia}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal by registered prostitutes in licensed brothels<br>Buying sex legal<br>Brothels legal and regulated<br>Procuring illegal<br>Solicitation illegal
}}
{{main|prostitution in Bolivia}}

In [[Bolivia]], prostitution is legal and regulated.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html|title=WORLD BRIEFING - THE AMERICAS; Bolivia: Prostitutes Sew Lips Together In Protest|first=|last=Reuters|date=25 October 2007|publisher=|accessdate=10 January 2017|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=zSyJAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA71&dq=Prostitution%20in%20Bolivia#v=onepage&q=Prostitution%20in%20Bolivia&f=false|title=CultureShock! Bolivia: A Survival Guide to Customs and Etiquette|first=Mark|last=Cramer|date=15 November 2009|publisher=Marshall Cavendish International Asia Pte Ltd|accessdate=10 January 2017|via=Google Books|isbn=9789814484350}}</ref> It is only permitted by registered prostitutes in licensed brothels.<ref name="spl" />  Prostitutes must register and must undergo regular health checks for sexually transmitted diseases (every 20 days). The police are allowed to check whether the prostitutes are registered or not, and have attended a clinic during the previous 20 days.<ref name="spl" />

In 2016 [[UNAIDS]] estimated there were 30,523 prostitutes in the country.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bolivia 2016 Country Factsheet|url=http://www.unaids.org/en/regionscountries/countries/bolivia/|website=UNAIDS|accessdate=22 April 2018|language=en}}</ref>
{{clear}}

===Brazil===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Brazil}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal<br>Buying sex legal<br>Brothels illegal<br>Procuring illegal<br>Solicitation illegal
}}
{{main|prostitution in Brazil}}

Prostitution that is the exchange of sex for money as there are no laws forbidding adults from being professional sex workers,<ref name="hrrpt">{{Citation
 | date = 2006-03-08
 | title = Brazil – Country Reports on Human Rights Practices – 2005
 | publisher = [[Bureau of Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor]] (USA Department of State)
 | url = https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2005/61718.htm
 | accessdate = 2008-08-08
}}</ref> but it is illegal to operate a [[brothel]] or to employ sex workers in any other way.<ref name=pbs>[https://www.pbs.org/newshour/health/aids/brazil/leite.html Gabriela Silva Leite], PBS Online NewsHour, 13 July 2003</ref> Public order and vagrancy laws are used against street prostitutes.<ref name="spl" /> The affordability of prostitutes is the most inquired-about term in word completion queries on purchases on Google.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/most-googled-products-in-one-map-a7457271.html|title=The most Googled products and services in every country in one crazy map|date=5 December 2016|publisher=}}</ref>

A 2013 survey published by [[UNAIDS]] estimated there to be 546,848 prostitutes in the country.<ref>{{cite web|title=Brazil 2016 Country Factshhet|url=http://www.unaids.org/en/regionscountries/countries/brazil/|website=UNAIDS|accessdate=22 April 2018|language=en}}</ref>
