===Guyana===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Guyana}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution illegal<br>Buying sex legal
}}
{{main|prostitution in Guyana}}

Prostitution is illegal but widespread.<ref name="spl" /> Prostitution law is antiquated and dates from the colonial era.<ref name="kempadoo" /> Law enforcement is inconsistent and sex workers report violence and abuse by the police.<ref name="spl" /><ref name="ngo">{{cite web|last1=Campbell|first1=Kurt|title=Calls mounted for legalization of Prostitution, regularization of sex work|url=http://www.inewsguyana.com/calls-mounted-for-legalization-of-prostitution-regularization-of-sex-work/|website=iNews Guyana|accessdate=24 December 2017|date=30 January 2014}}</ref> Many turn to prostitution for economic reasons and the lack of other job opportunities.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Jemmott|first1=Shauna|title=Lack of jobs forces students into prostitution, illegal activities – UNICEF report|url=http://guyanachronicle.com/2016/09/30/lack-of-jobs-forces-students-into-prostitution-illegal-activities-unicef-report|website=Guyana Chronicle|accessdate=24 December 2017|date=30 September 2016}}</ref> Prostitution continues to receive greater public attention due to the high incidence of [[HIV/AIDS]] among prostitutes.<ref>[https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2008/wha/119162.htm 2008 Human Rights Report: Guyana]. State.gov (2009-02-25). Retrieved on 2011-03-30.</ref> Prostitution in the country is separated into three types: "uptown", servicing affluent clients,<ref name="pellau" /> "downtown", servicing the working classes,<ref name="pellau">{{cite web|last1=Joseph|first1=Andrew|title=The Horniest Countries in the Caribbean|url=https://mypellau.com/2016/11/08/the-horniest-countries-in-the-caribbean/|website=Pellau Media|accessdate=22 December 2017|date=8 November 2016}}</ref> and mining sites.<ref>{{cite web|title=Guyana 2017 Trafficking in Persons Report|url=https://www.state.gov/j/tip/rls/tiprpt/countries/2017/271199.htm|publisher=U.S. Department of State Office to Monitor and Combat Trafficking in Persons|accessdate=24 December 2017}}</ref>
