===Suriname===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Suriname}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution illegal<br>Buying sex legal
}}
{{main|prostitution in Suriname}}

Prostitution is illegal<ref name="procon" /> but widespread and the laws are rarely enforced.<ref name="statesur">{{cite news|title= Country Reports on Human Rights Practices|publisher= [[U.S Department of State]]|date=|url= https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2002/18345.htm|accessdate=2008-06-29}}</ref> [[Human trafficking]]<ref name="statesur"/> and [[Child prostitution]]<ref name="pbssur"/> are problems in the country. Prostitutes are known locally as "motyo".

Although prostitution is illegal, the country issues temporary [[work permit]]s to migrant prostitutes travelling through Suriname en-route to another country.<ref name="pbssur">{{cite web |url= http://www.pbs.org/wnet/wideangle/uncategorized/human-trafficking-worldwide-suriname/1462/ |title= Human Trafficking Worldwide: Suriname |last= |first= |date= 25 September 2003 |website= Wideangle |publisher= |access-date= 2 December 2017 |quote= }}</ref>

Prostitutes often rent rooms in hotels and attract clients in the hotel's bar or outside the hotel.<ref name="kempadoo2">{{cite book|last1=Kempadoo|first1=Kamala|title=Sexing the Caribbean : gender, race, and sexual labor|date=2004|publisher=Routledge|location=New York [u.a.]|isbn=978-0415935036}}</ref>
{{clear}}

===Uruguay===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Uruguay}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal and regulated<br>Buying sex legal<br>Brothels legal and regulated<br>Procuring illegal<br>Solicitation restricted
}}
{{main|prostitution in Uruguay}}

Prostitution was legislated in 2002 through the sex work law (17.515).<ref name=law-17515>{{cite web|title=Law 16.832: ''Sex labour''|url=http://www.parlamento.gub.uy/leyes/AccesoTextoLey.asp?Ley=17515&Anchor=|publisher=[[Parliament of Uruguay]]|language=Spanish|date=July 9, 2002|accessdate=January 26, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150126184633/http://www.parlamento.gub.uy/leyes/AccesoTextoLey.asp?Ley=17515&Anchor=|archivedate=January 26, 2015}}</ref>
Before that, prostitution was unlegislated but it was not illegal, since the constitution allows any activity that is not forbidden by law.

UNAIDS estimate there to be 8,195 prostitutes in [[Uruguay]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Uruguay 2016 Country Factsheet|url=http://www.unaids.org/en/regionscountries/countries/uruguay|website=www.unaids.org|accessdate=26 April 2018|language=en}}</ref>
{{clear}}

===Venezuela===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Venezuela}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal and regulated<br>Buying sex legal<br>Brothels legal and regulated<br>Procuring illegal
}}
{{main|prostitution in Venezuela}}

Sex work in [[Venezuela]] is legal and regulated. The country's Ministry of Health and Social Development requires sex workers to carry identification cards and to have monthly health checkups. Prostitution is common, particularly in [[Caracas]] and in other domestic tourist destinations.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/story/0,,2229169,00.html|title=Tourism built on abuse|last=Bindel|first=Julie|date=2007-12-18|work=[[The Guardian]]|location=London|accessdate=2011-10-13}}</ref> The Venezuelan sex work industry arose in conjunction with the oil industry of the twentieth century and continues today.
{{clear}}

