In the capital, [[St. John's, Antigua and Barbuda|St. John's]], there is a [[red-light district]] in Popeshead Street.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Henry|first1=Brenton|title=MALE SEX WORKERS: A glimpse into their thriving, secret trade|url=https://antiguaobserver.com/male-sex-workers-a-glimpse-into-their-thriving-secret-trade/|website=Antigua Observer Newspaper|accessdate=19 March 2018|date=6 June 2013}}</ref> The most famous brothel in the street was Wendy's. It had operated for a number of years and was a household name on the island.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Beale|first1=Christopher|title=Antigua and Barbuda: Island Guide|date=2008|publisher=Other Places Publishing|isbn=9780615218373|url=https://books.google.com/?id=6aXxlwwEtAAC&pg=PT91&lpg=PT91&dq=Prostitution+in+Antigua+and+Barbuda#v=onepage&q=Prostitution%20in%20Antigua%20and%20Barbuda&f=false|language=en}}</ref> In 2016 the owners were charged with [[human trafficking|trafficking]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Wendy's Night Club Owners Charged with Human Trafficking|url=https://antiguachronicle.net/wendys-night-club-owners-charged-with-human-trafficking/|website=Antigua Chronicle|accessdate=19 March 2018|date=19 February 2016}}</ref> A 'rescue mission' raided the establishment in 2018, looking for trafficking victims. The nearby 'Jam Dung' was also raided.<ref>{{cite web|title=Authorities "rescue" strippers from local nightclubs|url=https://antiguanewsroom.com/news/crime/authorities-rescue-strippers-from-local-nightclubs/|website=Antigua News Room|accessdate=20 March 2018|date=10 February 2018}}</ref>
