Prostitution in Cuba has always been a legal profession, though it has periodically been regulated or repressed.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SKBvqXL0jTQC|title=Encyclopedia of Prostitution and Sex Work|first=Melissa Hope|last=Ditmore|year=2006|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=9780313329692|p=202}}</ref> Since the commencement of the [[Special Period]] in the early 1990s it has become associated with [[jineterismo]], a category of illegal or semi-legal economic activities related to [[tourism in Cuba]]. The low level of [[HIV/AIDS]] infection and the relatively inexpensive price of sex have made the island popular with foreigners as a sex tourism destination.<ref name=NYT>{{cite newspaper|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/12/26/world/americas/cuba-counters-prostitution-with-aids-programs.html|title=Cuba Counters Prostitution with AIDS Program|newspaper=The New York Times|date=26 December 2004|author=James C. Mckinley Jr.}}</ref>
