Prostitution is legal, but a third party may not derive financial gain from prostitution ([[brothels]] or similar establishments are illegal).<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2008/wha/119157.htm|title=2008 Human Rights Report: Dominican Republic|date=|website=Bureau of Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor|publisher=U.S. Department of State|accessdate=}}</ref>  However, the government usually does not enforce prostitution laws.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2009/wha/136110.htm |title=2009 Human Rights Report: Dominican Republic |publisher=State.gov |date=2010-03-11 |accessdate=2013-10-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Julia Scheeres |url=https://www.wired.com/techbiz/media/news/2001/07/44888 |title=The Web, Where 'Pimps' Roam Free |publisher=Wired.com |date= |accessdate=2013-10-12}}</ref>

It is estimated between 60,000 and [[Women in the Dominican Republic|100,000 women]] work as [[prostitutes]] in the country,<ref name="richest">{{cite web|title=10 Of The Most Popular Destinations For Sex Tourism|url=https://www.therichest.com/rich-list/most-popular/10-of-the-most-popular-destinations-for-sex-tourism/|website=The Richest|accessdate=14 December 2017|date=21 June 2014}}</ref><ref name="newsamerica">{{cite web|title=Popular Caribbean Sex Tourism Destinations|url=http://www.newsamericasnow.com/popular-caribbean-sex-tourism-destinations/|website=News America|accessdate=14 December 2017|date=27 May 2016}}</ref> many from neighbouring [[Prostitution in Haiti|Haiti]].<ref name="newsamerica" />
