Curaçao, Aruba, and Sint Maarten are destination islands for women trafficked for the sex trade from Peru, Brazil, Colombia, the Dominican Republic, and Haiti,<ref>{{cite web|title=Trafficking in Persons Report Country Narratives -- Countries H through R|url=https://www.state.gov/j/tip/rls/tiprpt/2008/105388.htm|publisher=United States Department of State Office to Monitor and Combat Trafficking in Persons|accessdate=23 December 2017|date=4 June 2008}}{{PD-notice}}</ref> In 2011, a human trafficking ring was broken up after trafficking women for sex exploitation from Colombia to Aruba, Curaçao, Sint Maarten, and Bonaire.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Maduro|first1=Letizia|title=A Situational Analysis of Aruba's Response to Human Trafficking|url=http://publications.iom.int/system/files/pdf/situational_analysis_aruba_10sep.pdf|publisher=International Organization for Migration|accessdate=23 December 2017|date=2013}}</ref>
