===Martinique===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Martinique}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal<br>Buying sex illegal<br>Brothels illegal<br>Procuring illegal<br>Solicitation illegal
}}
{{main|Prostitution in Overseas France#Martinique}}
The first laws on prostitution in [[Martinique]] were passed in the 1850s. They were designed to keep prostitutes away from public areas but poorly enforced.<ref name="sequin">{{cite web|last1=Sequin|first1=Caroline|title=Uprooting "Fleurs de Trottoirs":: Displacing Clandestine Prostitution and Negotiating Respectable Sex in Colonial Martinique 1938–47|url=https://aha.confex.com/aha/2017/webprogram/Paper20722.html|website=American Historical Association|accessdate=28 December 2017|date=7 January 2017}}</ref> In the 1930s, after the emergence of tourism and the start of [[WW2]], a new set of laws were enabled. The new laws targeted prostitution in the bars and restaurants of [[Fort-de-France]], which the colonial authorities believed were a major factor of [[Sexually transmitted infection|STIs]].<ref name="sequin" /> As a result, all waitresses and hostesses had to have a valid "certificat de non contagiosité", whether they were prostitutes or not. The aim of the authorities was to move all prostitution into brothels. The women were reluctant to work in the brothels, so prostitution remained in the bars and restaurants.<ref name="sequin" />
{{clear}}

===Montserrat===
{{Infobox
 |abovestyle = background:#cfc;
 |subheaderstyle = align-left
 |above        = {{Flagu|Montserrat}}
 |subheader    = Prostitution legal<br>Buying sex legal<br>Brothels illegal<br>Procuring illegal
}}
{{main|Prostitution in the British Overseas Territories#Montserrat}}
Prostitution in [[Montserrat]] is legal<ref name="montserratpenal">{{cite web|title=Montserrat Penal Code (Amendment) Act 2014|url=http://agc.gov.ms/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/No.-9-of-2014-Penal-Code-Amendment-Act-2014.pdf|website=Government of Montserrat|accessdate=25 February 2018}}</ref> and common.<ref name="fun">{{cite web|last1=Andrews|first1=Merrick|title=Prostitution in Montserrat 'Becoming a Fun Activity'|url=http://www.montserratreporter.org/news0302-2.htm|website=Montserrat Reporter|accessdate=25 February 2018}}</ref> However related activities such as controlling prostitution or living off the earnings of prostitution are prohibited by the Penal Code.<ref name="montserratpenal" />

Following the eruption of the [[Soufrière Hills Volcano]] in 1997 that buried the capital, [[Plymouth, Montserrat|Plymouth]], many migrant workers came to the island from Guyana, Jamaica, Haiti and the Dominican Republic.<ref name="guardianm">{{cite web|last1=Pattullo|first1=Polly|title=After the volcano|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2005/jul/18/g2.naturaldisasters|website=The Guardian|accessdate=25 February 2018|language=en|date=18 July 2005}}</ref> With them came prostitutes, especially from the Dominican Republic,<ref name="fun" /> and prostitution on the island increased.<ref name="guardianm" />
