Prostitution in the [[United States Virgin Islands|U.S. Virgin Islands]] is illegal<ref>{{cite web|title=Puerto Rico & the U. S. Virgin Islands Overview|url=http://netdwellers.com/mz/caribsexpert/blog_csx/Entries/2012/1/25_Puerto_Rico_%26_the_U._S._Virgin_Islands_Overview.html|website=Caribbean Sexpert|accessdate=22 April 2018|date=25 January 2012}}</ref> but occurs.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Surratt|first1=H.|title=Sex work in the Caribbean Basin: patterns of substance use and HIV risk among migrant sex workers in the US Virgin Islands|journal=AIDS Care|volume=19|issue=10|pmid=18071971|pages=1274–1282|doi=10.1080/09540120701426490|date=2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=St. Croix: Sex worker charged with attempted murder after stabbing client|url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/st-croix-sex-worker-charged-with-attempted-murder-after-stabbing-client/|website=St. Lucia News Online|accessdate=22 April 2018|language=en-us|date=27 August 2017}}</ref>

In 1985, 68 prostitutes were smuggled from [[Sint Maarten]] to [[Saint Thomas, U.S. Virgin Islands|Saint Thomas]] in the U.S. Virgin Islands in a sealed shipping container. 28 died of suffocation.<ref>{{cite web|title=28 Prostitutes Suffocate In Ship's Hold|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1985-04-21/news/8501230531_1_prostitutes-virgin-islands-guadeloupe|website=Chicago Tribune|accessdate=22 April 2018|language=en|date=April 21, 1985}}</ref>
